"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:6.13.1\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">6.13.1</span> Straps</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">שְׂרוֹךְ</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(srok)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen14:23\">GEN 14:23</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa5:27\">ISA 5:27</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">ἱμάς</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(himas)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark1:7\">MRK 1:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke3:16\">LUK 3:16</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John1:27\">JHN 1:27</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts22:25\">ACT 22:25</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description and usage:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>Straps were long, thin pieces of leather. They were put to many uses, including tying sandals, binding other things (that is, used like rope; see <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">1.14 Rope, cord&lt;REALIA:1.14&gt;</a>), or wielding as a whip (<a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">1.1.3 Whip, scourge&lt;REALIA:1.1.3&gt;</a>). See the illustrations at <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">6.13 Sandal, shoe&lt;REALIA:6.13&gt;</a>.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>In a number of languages the Greek word <em>himas</em> may be rendered “leather string” or “strip of leather.” In <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John1:27\">JHN 1:27</a> the term may be absorbed within the total expression at the end of the verse, for example, “I am not worthy to untie his sandals” (implying the untying of the straps with which the sandals were bound). This may be done in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark1:7\">MRK 1:7</a> and <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke3:16\">LUK 3:16</a> also.</p>\n<p>In <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts22:25\">ACT 22:25</a> two meanings are possible for the Greek word <em>himas</em>. Luke may either be telling the reason why Paul was being tied up or the means by which Paul was being tied up. So translators may render the first clause in this verse as “they tied him up with thongs” or “they tied him up for whipping,” in which case <em>himas</em> would refer to an event, not to an object.</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
